default3.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSince winter 2010/2011, signific
defaultant improvements have been made to how the aviation sector responds to major disruption.
default Below, the CAA has highlighted a number of these key improvements.
default3.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe CAA is continuing to work
default with the aviation industry, both in the UK and internationally,
default to ensure that it can maximise its contribution to improving winter resilience
default for the benefit of passengers
default. 
default3.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe CAA is currently undertaking a number of seminars for airlines and 
defaultgroundhandlers
default at Heathrow airport to ensure that the airport community, in particular non-EU airlines
default, who may not be as used to complying with the reg
defaultulations as EU ones
default, understands its legal obligations to passengers during periods of disruption. 
default3.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultTo ensure that if severe 
defaultdisuprtion
default does occur we have an accurate picture of compliance with the regulations across the country, t
defaulthe CAA is also expanding 
defaultits capability to observe disruption events first-hand so that it can cover a number of regional airports as well as airports around London. In addition, the CAA is currently engaging with the travel agent community to ensure that passengers that book via 
defaulta travel agent or other intermediary can be notified by the airline in the event of flight disruption. 
default3.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultOn the subject of passenger rights, the CAA and members of the BATA airlines group have developed a short, easy to understand leaflet on passenger right
defaults which this group of airlines have agreed to distribute to passengers in the event of flight cancellations or long delays. This is important to ensure that passengers are aware of what the airlines should be doing for them, and alongside our oversight wil
defaultl help to ensure that airlines comply with their obligations at all times.
default&#xa0;
default4.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAlthough the weather experienced
default during 
defaultwinter 2010/2011 was unusually severe, the last two winters have also been challenging.
default The fact that, despite
default these challenging conditions, we did not see a repeat of the major disruption in winter 2010/2011, 
defaulthighlights the benefits 
defaultof the improvements that have been made, in particular by 
defaultairports to improve their resilience to severe winter weather. 
defaultA
defaultirlines ha
defaultve played their part also, in particular through improving how they communicate with passengers when flights are cancelled or delayed, and also through improving the capability and flexibility for passengers to rebook 
defaultonline 
defaultwhen disruption does occur.
default4.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThi
defaults is not to say, of course, that there is no further room for improvement. Despite the significant improvement in resilience achieved by Heathrow airport since winter 2010/2011, 
defaultthe last two winters have seen significant disruption to British Airways
default’
default oper
defaultations at the airport, in particular at Terminal 5. 
defaultThe sheer scale, intensity, and complexity of British 
defaultAirways’ operation at the airport 
defaultmeans
default that it faces a number of unique challenges. 
defaultThese challenges are likely to be similar for any operator who ha
defaults a large proportion of operations at an airport, particularly if capacity is constrained, either at peaks or as with Heathrow generally.
default4.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWe believe that to 
defaultensure airlines who face these circumstances are prepared for them
default, there are series of steps that 
defaultcan be taken to ensure passengers are supported during disruption no matter how challenging the circumstances
default. These include, 
defaultensuring their systems for proactively contacting passengers about flight disruption are robust and they have correct contact details for their passengers; being 
defaultready
default 
defaultto deal effectively with 
defaultlarge and growing numbers of 
defaultpassengers when disruption occurs 
default(for instance avoiding long queues for all passengers by breaking them into groups based on their flight’s status and ease of rebooking); making sure their all their staff have the same 
defaultinformation to handle customer queries,
default and 
defaultthat
default information is up-to-
defaultdate.
default 
default4.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn addition, 
defaultin circumstances where airlines have a large fleet operating from a single airport, there are also particular operational challenges, for instance in terms of de-icing, 
defaultwhich they need to ensure they are ready for during future severe w
defaulteather events.
default4.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultTo ensure that they are prepared for future events, and that disruption to passengers is minimised, th
defaulte CAA continues to work closely with 
defaultUK and foreign airlines to 
defaultensure they are addressing these issues
