default5.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Civil Aviation Act 2012 allows much more flexible regulation as rules will be set within a licence that can be amended (subject to due process). On 3 October 2013 the CAA published our final proposals for regulation at Heathrow and Gatwick if we make a
default final decision in January that these airports have substantial market power that requires regulation. 
default5.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultConsistent with better regulation principles, we have not sought to regulate for all eventualities but pick only key priorities for inclusion in the fir
defaultst licences granted to the airports. 
default5.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultBecause we understand how important service quality during disruption is to passengers, one of the first licence conditions will strengthen each airport’s approach to operational resilience. The rules will ensure that 
defaultthe airport has robust plans to deal with disruption, and an effective approach to collaboration; and will ensure full communication with affected passengers.
default 
default5.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWe are in the process of consulting on our Final Proposals for 
defaultregulation for the period after A
defaultpril 2014. 
defaultThese licence conditions are part of that consultation. 
defaultThe licences would come into force on 1 April 2014 so will not have an effect this winter, but plans and processes should be in place by October 2014
default to ensure that by winter 2014 regulated
default airports have a licence-condition obliging them
default to
default strengthen their readiness for disruption
default for the first time
default.
default5.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis condition would mean that if the airports failed to have adequate provisions in place 
defaultto deal with 
defaultdisruption 
defaultto their operations or had 
defaultnot followed their plans
default, and the CAA judged that more could have been done 
defaultby the airport 
defaultto protect passengers from the impact, they could be subject to fines, 
defaultpotentially up to 10% of 
defaultthe airport
default’
defaults
default turnover.
